'''Block Inc.''' is an American [[public company]] founded in 2009 by [[Jack Dorsey]] and [[Jim McKelvey]]. Initially named '''Square Inc.''','''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Browning |first1=Kellen |date=1 December 2021 |title=Square, Jack Dorsey's payments company, changes its name to Block. |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/01/technology/square-block-name-change-dorsey.html?action=click&module=Well&pgtype=Homepage&section=Technology |access-date=2 December 2021}}</ref>''' the company comprises various businesses within the [[Fintech|financial technology]] sector. Block’s service network reportedly includes nearly 4 million merchants and 51 million users, as of 2023.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

Block's inaugural product [[Square (payment system)|Square]] is a credit card payment platform which enables [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|small and medium-sized businesses]] to use smartphones or [[Tablet computer|tablets]] as [[point-of-sale]] registers<ref name=":2" /> and to manage operations such as bookings,<ref name=":3" /> [[E-commerce|e-Commerce]],<ref name=":4" /> inventory,<ref name=":5" /> payroll, shift schedules,<ref name=":6" /> banking, and borrowing [[Business loan|business loans]].<ref name=":7" /> Block’s portfolio includes [[Cash App]], which offers [[peer-to-peer transaction|peer-to-peer transactions]], [[direct deposit|direct deposits]],<ref name=":8" /><ref name=":9" /> a savings account, a debit card, investing in stocks and [[Bitcoin]],<ref name=":10" /><ref name=":11" /> a tax filing service,<ref name=":12" /> and [[personal loans]].<ref name=":13" /> Block also owns [[Afterpay]], a [[buy now, pay later]] service;<ref name=":14" /> TBD, a [[Decentralized web|decentralized platform]] targeting Bitcoin and [[decentralized finance]];<ref name=":15">{{Cite web |last=Lowrey |first=Annie |date=2023-06-17 |title=Is Crypto Dead? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/crypto-down-or-it-dead/674442/ |access-date=2023-12-12 |website=The Atlantic |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":16">{{Cite web |last=Adams |first=Michael |date=2023-12-01 |title=6 Best Cryptocurrency Stocks Of December 2023 – Forbes Advisor |url=https://www.forbes.com/advisor/investing/cryptocurrency/best-cryptocurrency-stocks/ |access-date=2023-12-12 |website=www.forbes.com}}</ref> [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], a subscription-based [[Music streaming|music streaming service]];<ref name=":17" /> and [[Weebly]], a [[web hosting service|web hosting]] provider.

==History==
The original inspiration for Square occurred to [[Jack Dorsey]] in 2009 when his friend [[Jim McKelvey]] was unable to complete a $2,000 sale of his glass faucets and fittings because he could not accept credit cards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 11, 2010 |title=Square Brings Credit Card Swiping to the Mobile Masses, Starting Today |url=http://www.fastcompany.com/1643271/square-brings-credit-card-swiping-mobile-masses-starting-today |access-date=September 19, 2011 |website=Fast Company}}</ref> Co-founders Dorsey—who also co-founded [[Twitter, Inc.|Twitter]]—and McKelvey began developing the company out of a small office in St. Louis.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2015-09-15 |title=Why Square's New Office Is A Really Big Deal for St. Louis |url=https://www.stlmag.com/news/why-square-new-office-is-a-really-big-deal-for-st-louis/ |work=St. Louis Magazine}}</ref> The name "Square" derives from the company's square-shaped card readers.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2011-05-26 |title=Square's name and design were changed by a lunch at Apple |url=https://thenextweb.com/apple/2011/05/26/squares-name-and-design-were-changed-by-a-lunch-at-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=thenextweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=May 26, 2011 |title=Square Was Almost Named Squirrel Until Dorsey Talked To Apple |url=http://pulse2.com/2011/05/26/square-was-almost-named-squirrel-until-dorsey-talked-to-apple/ |access-date=September 19, 2011 |publisher=pulse2.com}}</ref>

In October 2020, Square put approximately 1% of their total assets ($50 million) in [[Bitcoin]] (4,709 bitcoins), citing Bitcoin's "potential to be a more ubiquitous currency in the future" as their main reasoning.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Oliver Effron |title=Square just bought $50 million in bitcoin |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/10/08/business/square-bitcoin-crypto-investment/index.html |access-date=2020-10-22 |website=CNN|date=8 October 2020 }}</ref> The company purchased approximately 3,318 bitcoins in February 2021 for a cost of around $170 million, bringing Square's total holdings to around 8,027 bitcoins (equivalent to around US$500 million in 2021, around US$190 million as of February 2023).<ref>{{Cite web|last=Bursztynsky|first=Jessica|date=2021-02-23|title=Square buys $170 million worth of bitcoin|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/23/square-buys-170-million-worth-of-bitcoin.html|access-date=2021-03-02|website=CNBC|language=en}}</ref>

On March 2, 2021, Square reached an agreement to acquire majority ownership in [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]. Square paid $297 million in cash and stock for Tidal, with [[Jay-Z]] joining the company's board of directors. Jay-Z, as well as other artists who currently own stock in Tidal, will remain stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |title=Square, Inc. to buy majority of Tidal and put Jay-Z on board |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/square-buy-majority-tidal-put-jay-board-76248384 |work=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |access-date=4 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murphy Kelly |first1=Samantha |title=Square to acquire majority stake in music service Tidal for $297 million |date=4 March 2021 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/03/04/tech/square-tidal/index.html |publisher=CNN |access-date=4 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Singleton |first1=Micah |title=Square Is Acquiring a Majority Stake in Tidal for $297M |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/streaming/9534646/square-tidal-acquisition-majority-stake-jay-z |magazine=Billboard |access-date=5 March 2021}}</ref>

On December 1, 2021, Square announced that it would change its company name to Block, Inc. on December 10.<ref name=wsj_block>{{Cite news|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=2021-12-01|title=Square Changes Name to Block, Days After CEO Jack Dorsey Leaves Twitter|language=en-US|work=Wall Street Journal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/square-changes-name-to-block-days-after-ceo-jack-dorsey-leaves-twitter-11638394200|access-date=2021-12-01|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release|date=2021-12-01|title=Square, Inc. Changes Name to Block|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20211201006139/en/Square-Inc.-Changes-Name-to-Block|access-date=2021-12-01|publisher=Block, Inc.|via=[[Business Wire]]|language=en}}</ref> The change was announced shortly after Dorsey resigned as CEO of Twitter.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Kurt |title=Square Changes Name to Block in Nod to New Businesses |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-01/dorsey-s-square-changes-name-to-block-in-nod-to-new-businesses?sref=CIpmV6x8 |access-date=2 December 2021 |work=Bloomberg |date=1 December 2021}}</ref> On December 10, 2021, the name change took effect, and Square, Inc. became Block, Inc..<ref name="cnbc.com">{{cite web |title=Jack Dorsey's Square changes corporate name to Block |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/01/square-changes-corporate-name-to-block-.html |access-date=10 December 2021 |website=CNBC}}</ref> On December 16, less than a week into the rebrand, [[H&R Block]], sued the company for [[trademark infringement]], claiming that the name seeks to confuse customers by misappropriating the Block brand name, which H&R owns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-16/h-r-block-claims-jack-dorsey-s-block-inc-violates-trademark| title=H&R Block Is Suing Jack Dorsey's Block Over Name Change |website=Bloomberg |access-date=December 16, 2021}}</ref> The lawsuit was resolved in April 2023 when the two companies jointly agreed to dismiss the suit.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brittain |first=Blake |date=2023-04-24 |title=H&R Block settles trademark lawsuit against Block over name change |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/legal/hr-block-agrees-drop-trademark-lawsuit-against-block-over-name-change-2023-04-24/ |access-date=2023-09-30}}</ref>

On January 31, 2022, Block completed its acquisition of [[Afterpay]].<ref name="completed acquistion"/>

==Subsidiaries, products, services==

===Square===
{{Main|Square (payment system)}}
Square is a payments platform aimed at small and medium businesses that allows them to accept credit card payments and use smartphones or tablets or computers as payment registers for a [[Point-of-sale|point-of-sale system]] (POS).<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Morrison |first=Sara |date=2022-10-07 |title=Everyone wants a tip now. Do you have to give them one? |url=https://www.vox.com/recode/2022/10/7/23389885/square-toast-tipping-retail-tipflation-guilt |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-11 |title=Square POS Reviews & Ratings 2023 |url=https://www.trustradius.com/products/square-pos/reviews |access-date=2023-11-02 |website=www.trustradius.com |language=en-US}}</ref> The platform was founded in 2009 by Dorsey and McKelvey. Square also offers additional features to manage various operations including staff payroll and shift schedules,<ref name=":6">{{Cite web |last=O'Reilly |first=Dennis |date=2023-05-25 |title=Square Payroll Software Review and Prices |url=https://www.usnews.com/360-reviews/business/payroll-software/block |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref> customer bookings,<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Sherman |first=Matt |date=2023-10-24 |title=Square Appointments Review |url=https://www.merchantmaverick.com/reviews/square-appointments-review/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=Merchant Maverick |language=en}}</ref> inventory, e-Commerce,<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Amy Nichol |date=2022-02-22 |title=Square Online Store Review 2023: Features, Pros & Cons – Forbes Advisor |url=https://www.forbes.com/advisor/business/software/square-online-review/ |access-date=2023-11-03 |website=www.forbes.com}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Stevens |first=Courtenay |date=2022-12-14 |title=Everything You Need to Know about Square Inventory Management |url=https://www.business.org/finance/inventory-management/square-inventory-review/ |access-date=2023-11-03 |website=Business.org |language=en-US}}</ref> banking and business loans.<ref name=":7">{{Cite news |last=Irrera |first=Anna |date=2021-07-20 |title=Square launches small business banking |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/square-launches-small-business-banking-2021-07-20/ |access-date=2023-10-30}}</ref>

In 2022, a [[Protocol (website)|Protocol]] survey showed that 35% of U.S. small business owners used Square, a higher percentage than its competitors in the survey, while also highlighting the POS market's continued fragmentation. <ref>{{Cite web |last=Geron |first=Tomio |date=2022-01-05 |title=Square, Clover and Lightspeed are popular, but no POS provider dominates - Protocol |url=https://www.protocol.com/fintech/small-business-fintech-survey-2022/small-business-survey-pos |access-date=2023-11-16 |website=www.protocol.com |language=en}}</ref> In April 2023, Square was reported to have four million merchants as its customers.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Mullen |first=Caitlin |date=2023-04-18 |title=Square rolls out new features for merchants |url=https://www.retaildive.com/news/square-rolls-out-new-features-block-payments-merchant-services-smbs/647580/ |access-date=2023-11-15 |website=Retail Dive |language=en-US}}</ref> 

===Cash App===
{{Main|Cash App}}

Launched in October 2013, [[Cash App]] (formerly Square Cash) allows person-to-person money transfer via the app or website.<ref name=":8">{{Cite web |last=Hamburger |first=Ellis |date=2013-10-15 |title=Square Cash lets anyone with a debit card send money instantly over email |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/10/15/4842518/square-cash-send-money-over-email-iphone-android |access-date=2020-12-20 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite web |last=Freitas |first=Taylor |date=2022-04-29 |title=What is Cash App and how does it work? |url=https://www.zdnet.com/finance/what-is-cash-app-and-how-does-it-work-a-comprehensive-guide/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref> In March 2015, the firm introduced Square Cash for businesses, which includes the ability for individuals, organizations, and business owners to use a unique username, known as a $cashtag, to send and receive money.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 23, 2015 |title=Square Introduces Square Cash for Businesses, With a Low 1.5 Percent Processing Fee |url=http://recode.net/2015/03/23/square-introduces-square-cash-for-businesses-with-a-low-1-5-percent-processing-fee/ |work=Re/code}}</ref> As of 2023, Cash App also offers a savings account and a debit card, and services such as direct deposit and investing in stocks and Bitcoin.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |last=Staples |first=Ana |date=2023-08-22 |title=What is Cash App and how does it work? |url=https://www.cnbc.com/select/what-is-cash-app/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":11">{{Cite web |last=Papandrea |first=Dawn |date=2023-08-28 |title=How to Use Cash App |url=https://www.usnews.com/banking/articles/how-to-use-cash-app |website=[[U.S. News & World Report]]}}</ref> In March 2023, [[USA Today]] reported that Cash App offered a free tax-filing service while cautioning that it didn't accommodate "every tax situation" and didn't offer "live tax support".<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Jenn |date=2023-09-11 |title=Best tax software of November 2023 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/blueprint/taxes/best-tax-software/ |access-date=2023-11-09 |website=USA TODAY Blueprint |language=en-US}}</ref> In October 2023, it was reported that Cash App also allowed users to borrow up to $200 from the app, and that "not everyone is an eligible user for this feature".<ref name=":13">{{Cite web |last=Moorhead |first=Caitlyn |date=2023-10-16 |title=Cash App Borrow: How To Borrow Money on Cash App |url=https://www.gobankingrates.com/banking/technology/cash-app-borrow/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=GOBankingRates |language=en}}</ref>

In February 2023, Block reported 51 million "monthly active users" for Cash App.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Hollerith |first=David |date=2023-02-23 |title=Block reports revenue, profits that top expectations amid bitcoin drag |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/block-reports-revenue-profits-that-top-expectations-amid-bitcoin-drag-183916769.html |access-date=2023-11-15 |website=Yahoo Finance |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=PYMNTS |date=2023-05-05 |title=Block's Cash App Hits 53 Million Monthly Active Users, Direct Deposits up 69% |url=https://www.pymnts.com/news/mobile-payments/2023/block-cash-app-hits-53-million-monthly-active-users-direct-deposits-up-69-percent/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=www.pymnts.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

===Afterpay===
{{Main|Afterpay}}
Afterpay is an Australian digital payment platform in which a bought product can be paid off in four installments. This idea made in 2008 by a then eighteen-year-old Nick Molnar was geared towards millennials and inspired by the aftermath of the 2008 Global Financial Crisis. Molnar and Partner/ Co-founder Anthony Eisen launched their platform in 2014 and in four years their product reached a market capitalization of around $3.3 billion. In February 2020, Afterpay was reported to have 3.6 million active customers in the US, 3.1 million in Australia and New Zealand, and 600,000 in the UK. In August 2021, Afterpay and Square announced that Afterpay would be acquired by Square.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-08-01 |title=Afterpay to be acquired by Square in $39 billion deal |url=https://www.smartcompany.com.au/startupsmart/news/afterpay-acquired-square-39-billion/ |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=SmartCompany |language=en-US}}</ref> Block paid US$29 billion in stock for the acquisition and the process was finalized in January 2022.<ref name="completed acquistion">{{cite press release|title=Block, Inc. Completes Acquisition of Afterpay|url=https://investors.block.xyz/news/news-details/2022/Block-Inc.-Completes-Acquisition-of-Afterpay/default.aspx|publisher=Block, Inc.|date=January 31, 2022}}</ref><ref name=":14">{{Cite web |last=Gariffo |first=Michael |date=2022-02-01 |title=Block completes acquisition of "buy now, pay later" specialist Afterpay |url=https://www.zdnet.com/finance/block-completes-acquisition-of-buy-now-pay-later-specialist-afterpay/ |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref> Although Afterpay is now owned by Block inc., Molnar and Eisen still spearhead Afterpay's merchant and consumer businesses.

=== Tidal ===
{{Main|Tidal (service)}}

Tidal is a digital music streaming service that gives users access to over 80 million songs from genres and artists across the world.<ref name="Pocket-lint">{{Cite web |last=Pocket-lint |date=2022-02-03 |title=What is Tidal and how does it work? |url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/apps/news/133451-what-is-tidal-and-why-should-you-care |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=www.pocket-lint.com |language=en-gb}}</ref> Tidal was founded on the basis of artists getting paid rightfully for their work, meaning fully and directly instead of through traditional means. Tidal was first launched in 2014 by a Norwegian company called Aspiro. Aspiro was purchased by Jay-Z in 2015 for $56 million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sisario |first=Ben |date=2015-03-13 |title=Jay Z Buys the Music Streaming Firm, Aspiro |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/14/business/media/jay-z-buys-the-music-streaming-firm-aspiro.html |access-date=2022-04-25 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In early 2017, the Sprint Corporation purchased 33% of the company for $200 million and then in 2021 Square Inc. paid $297 million for a majority ownership of the company.<ref name=":17">{{Cite web |last=Rosman |first=Katherine |date=2021-03-04 |title=Square Acquires Tidal in $297 Million Deal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/04/business/media/tidal-square-jay-z-dorsey.html |access-date=2023-10-30 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US}}</ref> Tidal now operates in 61 countries worldwide.<ref name="Pocket-lint" /> In June, 2022, through the disclosure of the Annual Stockholder Meeting 2022, Block reported that the stake acquired in the Tidal music service was 86.8%.<ref name="AnnualStockholderMeeting2022">{{Cite web |title=Page 188 from Block, Inc. Annual Stockholder Meeting 2022 |url=https://s29.q4cdn.com/628966176/files/doc_presentations/2022/06/Block-Annual-Report-2022.pdf}}</ref>

=== TBD ===
TBD is a Bitcoin-focussed subsidiary of Block.<ref name=":15" /> TBD serves as a [[Decentralized web|decentralized platform]] which allows developers to build [[decentralized finance]] (DeFi) applications to run on programmable [[Blockchain|blockchains]].<ref name=":16" />

=== Weebly ===
{{Main|Weebly}}
[[Weebly]] is a [[web hosting service]]. Weebly was founded in 2006 by David Rusenko, Dan Veltri, and Chris Fanini after they all met as students at Pennsylvania State University.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Levy |first=Steven |date=2007-05-20 |title=A Boot Camp for the Next Tech Billionaires |url=https://www.newsweek.com/boot-camp-next-tech-billionaires-100977 |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=Newsweek |language=en}}</ref> In 2007, Weebly raised $650,000 in initial capital from a group of angel investors. In 2018, Square Inc. (Now Block Inc.) bought Weebly in exchange for $365 million in cash and stock.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Square is acquiring website builder Weebly for $365M |url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2018/04/26/square-acquires-weebly/ |access-date=2022-04-25 |website=TechCrunch |date=26 April 2018 |language=en-US }}{{Dead link|date=October 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The company slowly grew and updated its capabilities over the course of a decade and now Weebly is a free online website creator that operates out of the web browser. The site offers users access to drag and drop features to build their websites, with unlimited storage options and custom URLs.

==Financials==
Square received [[Angel investor|angel investments]] from [[Marissa Mayer]], [[Kevin Rose]], [[Biz Stone]], [[Dennis Crowley]], [[Shawn Fanning]], [[MC Hammer]], and [[Esther Dyson]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} Since then, it has raised several additional rounds of funding:
* Series A funding from [[Khosla Ventures]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series B funding from [[Sequoia Capital]]<ref name=rounds />
* Series C funding from [[Kleiner Perkins]]<ref name=rounds>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/11/09/square-ipo-will-net-big-win-for-one-firm.html |title=On paper, Khosla's firm could net a massive return on Square IPO |date=9 November 2015 |work=[[CNBC]] |last=Taylor |first=Harriet}}</ref>
