==Business==

===Operations===
Block was co-founded by [[Twitter]] creator Jack Dorsey under the name Square.<ref name="aboutsquare">{{Cite web |title=About Square |url=https://squareup.com/about |access-date=March 15, 2011 |publisher=Square Inc.}}</ref> Dorsey also serves as [[chief executive officer]] and Amrita Ahuja serves as [[chief financial officer]].<ref name="aboutsquare" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Want |first=Selina |date=3 January 2019 |title=Square Names Activision Blizzard's Ahuja as Finance Chief |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-03/square-names-activision-blizzard-s-amrita-ahuja-as-finance-chief |url-status=live |access-date=2019-01-28 |website=Bloomberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601071255/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-03/square-names-activision-blizzard-s-amrita-ahuja-as-finance-chief |archive-date=2019-06-01 }}</ref> Block's office is in [[San Francisco]].<ref name="californiahomedesign1">{{Cite web |last=Evangelista |first=Benny |date=October 14, 2013 |title=New offices give Square workers lots of options |url=http://www.sfgate.com/business/article/New-offices-give-Square-workers-lots-of-options-4892854.php |access-date=January 6, 2014 |website=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> The firm has more than 5,000 employees.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Block Inc - Company Profile and News - Bloomberg Markets |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/company/SQ:US |access-date=January 18, 2022 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref>

Block's payment platform, Square, has been available in the United States since 2010 and the company launched in Canada at the end of 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Matt Hartley |date=October 24, 2012 |title=Square launches in Canada |work=[[Financial Post]] |url=http://business.financialpost.com/fp-tech-desk/square-launches-in-canada?__lsa=eca6-41b8 |access-date=October 24, 2012}}</ref> In March 2020, Square implemented [[remote work]] due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]]. In May 2020, Square announced that some of its workers would be allowed to be permanent [[remote work]]ers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Petrin |first=Kae M. |title=Square Adopts Permanent Work-From-Home Policy For Workers In St. Louis, Nationwide |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/square-adopts-permanent-work-home-policy-workers-st-louis-nationwide |access-date=2020-06-03 |website=[[KWMU]] |date=19 May 2020 |language=en}}</ref> As of 2021, although Block's real estate footprint remains intact, they no longer have a designated headquarters location.<ref name="10K2021" />

===Financing and acquisitions===
In August 2014, Victory Park Capital, an asset management firm, invested in Square Capital.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 19, 2014 |title=Square works with Victory Park Capital to extend hundreds of millions of dollars to independent businesses |url=http://www.victoryparkcapital.com/news/news_2014_square_works_with_VPC.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713220348/http://www.victoryparkcapital.com/news/news_2014_square_works_with_VPC.shtml |archive-date=July 13, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015 |publisher=Victory Park Capital |df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2015, Square Capital raised additional funding, with Victory Park Capital tripling its initial investment.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Square secures funding from new and existing investors to expand its popular small business financing program |url=https://squareup.com/news/capital-investment |date=May 12, 2015 |access-date=July 13, 2015 |publisher=Square, Inc.}}</ref> As of 2016, Square had loaned $1 billion to companies through Square Capital since the program's inception.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Yeung |first=Ken |date=1 November 2016 |title=Square has provided more than $1 billion in loans to businesses |url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/01/square-has-provided-more-than-1-billion-in-loans-to-businesses/ |work=VentureBeat |access-date=3 November 2016}}</ref> On November 19, 2015, Square Inc. became a [[public company]] via an [[initial public offering]].<ref name="nypost">{{Cite web |date=2015-11-19 |title=Square shakes off weak IPO with first-day trading pop |url=https://nypost.com/2015/11/19/square-shakes-off-weak-ipo-with-first-day-trading-pop/ |access-date=19 November 2015 |website=New York Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Soper |first=Alex Barinka alexbarinka Spencer |title=Square Files for IPO as CEO Dorsey Juggles Twitter Revamp |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-14/square-files-for-ipo-as-ceo-dorsey-juggles-twitter-revamp |access-date=2015-10-16 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref> On April 19, 2018, Square announced that it had acquired Zesty, a [[food delivery]] service that caters to corporate offices.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bary |first=Emily |title=Square acquires food-delivery platform Zesty to boost office-catering business |language=en-US |work=MarketWatch |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/square-acquires-food-delivery-platform-zesty-to-boost-office-catering-business-2018-04-19 |access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Carson |first=Biz |title=Square's Delivery Business Caviar Moves Into Corporate Catering With Acquisition Of Zesty |language=en |work=Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bizcarson/2018/04/19/caviar-acquires-zesty-office-lunch/#760d66f41ae3 |access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref> On April 26, 2018, Square announced that it would acquire [[Weebly]], a website-building service, for $365 million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Balakrishnan |first=Anita |date=2018-04-26 |title=Square to buy Weebly for $365 million |work=CNBC |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/26/square-to-buy-weebly-for-365-million.html |access-date=2018-04-27}}</ref> In May 2019, Square announced that it had acquired Eloquent Labs, an artificial intelligence startup helping improve the customer service experience.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 May 2019 |title=Square acquires conversational AI startup Eloquent Labs |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/07/square-acquires-conversational-ai-startup-eloquent-labs/ |access-date=2019-05-08 |website=TechCrunch |language=en-US}}{{Dead link|date=October 2023|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>

In February 2020, Square announced that it had acquired Dessa, a Toronto-based deep learning company.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-02-07 |title=Square acquires deepfake research firm Dessa |url=https://venturebeat.com/2020/02/07/square-acquires-deepfakes-research-firm-dessa-labs-for-an-undisclosed-sum/ |access-date=2020-05-21 |website=VentureBeat |language=en-US}}</ref> In November 2020, Square announced it was acquiring Credit Karma Tax, a free do-it-yourself tax-filing service, from [[Credit Karma]] for $50 million and would make it a part of its Cash App unit.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Weil |first=Dan |date=2020-11-25 |title=Square to Buy Credit Karma Tax for $50 Million, Expanding Reach |url=https://www.thestreet.com/investing/square-buying-credit-karma-tax-for-50-million |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206220849/https://www.thestreet.com/investing/square-buying-credit-karma-tax-for-50-million |archive-date=2020-12-06 |access-date=2020-12-20 |website=TheStreet}}</ref> In March 2021, Square announced it was acquiring a significant majority in music streaming platform [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] for $293 million in a deal of stock and cash.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rosman|first=Katherine|date=2021-03-04|title=Square acquires majority of Tidal, Jay-Z's streaming service, in $297 million deal.|language=en-US|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/04/business/media/tidal-square-jay-z-dorsey.html|access-date=2021-06-08|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the same month, Square's Q1 sales surged 266% as transactions jumped amid economic recovery.<ref>{{Cite web|last=McCormick|first=Emily|date=May 6, 2021|title=Square Q1 sales surge 266% as transactions jump amid economic recovery, bitcoin revenue soars|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/topstocks/square-q1-earnings-set-to-show-pick-up-in-transactions-amid-economic-recovery-surge-in-bitcoin-revenue/ar-BB1gqwo9|url-status=live|access-date=2021-06-08|work=Yahoo! Finance |via=MSN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608110718/https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/topstocks/square-q1-earnings-set-to-show-pick-up-in-transactions-amid-economic-recovery-surge-in-bitcoin-revenue/ar-BB1gqwo9 |archive-date=2021-06-08 }}</ref> In August 2021, Square announced its acquisition of [[Afterpay]], a company offering a "[[buy now, pay later]]" service. Square finalized the $29 billion stock deal on January 31, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Peters |first=Jay |date=August 1, 2021 |title=Square to buy Afterpay, which offers a 'buy now, pay later' service, for $29 billion in stock |url=https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/1/22605025/square-afterpay-acquisition-buy-now-pay-later-service-29-billion-stock |url-status=live |access-date=2021-08-02 |website=The Verge|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210801224942/https://www.theverge.com/2021/8/1/22605025/square-afterpay-acquisition-buy-now-pay-later-service-29-billion-stock |archive-date=2021-08-01 }}</ref><ref name="completed acquistion"/>

== Controversies ==

=== Allegations of illegal activity ===
On March 23, 2023, investment research firm [[Hindenburg Research]] disclosed a [[Short (finance)|short position]] in Block, leading to a 15% drop in the company's shares that day. Hindenburg's accusations of Block included exaggerating user counts, failing to curb fraud and illegal activity on [[Cash App]], and permitting impersonation of high-profile individuals. It also wrote in its report that Block "embraced predatory offerings and compliance worst practices in order to fuel growth and profit from facilitation of fraud against consumers and the government."<ref>{{cite web |date=March 23, 2023 |title=Hindenburg takes aim at Dorsey's payments firm Block, shares plunge |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/hindenburg-shorts-jack-dorseys-payments-firm-block-2023-03-23/ |accessdate=May 12, 2023 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=de la Merced |first=Michael J. |date=March 23, 2023 |title=Short Seller Accuses Jack Dorsey's Block of Facilitating Fraud |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/03/23/business/dealbook/hindenburg-block-jack-dorsey.html}}</ref>

Block responded to the allegations in a press release saying, "We intend to work with the SEC and explore legal action against Hindenburg Research for the factually inaccurate and misleading report they shared about our Cash App business today".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goswami |first1=Rohan |last2=Sigalos |first2=MacKenzie |date=2023-03-23 |title=Block shares plunge 19% after short seller Hindenburg says Jack Dorsey's company facilitates fraud |work=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2023/03/23/block-shares-plunge-after-hindenburg-says-jack-dorseys.html |accessdate=2023-03-23}}</ref>

